rovoking analysis, Farley develops themes that include childhood loss, the myth of innocence, the problem of diagnosis, the subject of racial hatred, the meaning of a good fight, and gender embodiment. She draws extensively on psychoanalytic concepts to show how the fantasy of the child advancing through lockstep stages fails to account for the child as symbolic of the conflicts of entering into the social world. Childhood beyond Pathology suggests we reconsider developmental understandings of childhood by honoring the elusive qualities of inner life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aChild development. 0aChild psychology. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aEducation : Early Childhood Studies. 4aEducation : Education. 4aGender and Sexuality : Queer Studies. 4aPsychology : Psychoanalysis. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Developmental / Child.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847092440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438470924423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438470924/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles